This paper proposes a physics-informed machine learning method to predict the time average of a chaotic attractor. The method is based on the hybrid echo state network (hESN). The paper combines concepts from physics and machine learning, making it likely to belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. The paper also involves the use of machine learning techniques, making it likely to belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. The paper deals with the prediction of time-averaged quantities in chaotic systems, making it likely to belong to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. The paper also involves the study of chaotic systems, making it likely to belong to the cs.DS (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of physical models to improve the accuracy of the prediction, making it likely to belong to the cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) sub-category.
